sachin gupta wrote:

&gt; You use Junit in the same way for integration tests as for unit tests . The
&gt; only difference is that while writing Unit tests you will have to write
&gt; pseudo Classes, that a method you are testing, refers to, while in
&gt; Integration testing you replace these pseudo classes by the actual classes.
&gt; In unit testing you control the input that will come from the interacting
&gt; classes while in integration testing the values are actually
&gt; computed/fetched by the objects/classes.
&gt;
&gt; There are two cases:
&gt;
&gt; First, when you have been writing unit tests for each class in JUnit from
&gt; the start. In this case the &quot;Test suite&quot; that includes test classes will
&gt; serve the purpose you are looking for in integration testing framework.
&gt;
&gt; Second, you have not written any tests for your classes till now and now you
&gt; need to change a class that interacts with other classes. In this case I
&gt; will suggest you to write test cases for this class and test it thoroughly.
&gt; Next you will need to trace the interaction of this class (maybe from the
&gt; design document) with other classes and write test to ensure that the
&gt; requirements are met.
&gt;
&gt; If the system design is OO and the design document is well done, all you
&gt; will need to understand are the responsibilities of this class of objects
&gt; and modify accordingly.
&gt;
&gt; Regards,
&gt;
&gt; Sachin
